Title: How to use this REST connector
Content:
How to use this REST connector - A `POST` request to the API should contain `body` content with a `JSON` object containing all the required information for the target API and instructions for loops (when appropriate). A simple `JSON` payload should look as per the example below -

```json
{
    "uri":"https://myexampleapi.com/v0/[BASE ID]/[TABLE NAME]/"    
}
```

API currently has the following options

- [URI](#uri)
- [Method](#method)
- [Headers](#headers)
- [Authentication](#authentication)
- [Parameters](#parameters)
- [Body](#body)
- [Loop](#loop)
- [Pagination](#pagination)
- [Storage](#storage)

Title: URI
Content:
URI - This is the full or end point `URL` for the API you wish to call.

Example of a basic static `URL` for a single endpoint

```json
{
    "uri":"https://myexampleapi.com/v0/baseid/tablename/"
}
```

When using `loop` option and require the API `URL` to be dynamic, then use `{}` to represent the dynamic part of the `URL`.

Example of a dynamic `URL`

```json
{ 
    "uri":"https://myexampleapi.com/v0/[BASE ID]/{0}/{1}/"
}
```

The above example contains to dynamic parts (`{}` and `{}`). The number represent the index for the dynamic values. See the loop section for more details.

Title: Method
Content:
Method - `Method` parameter indicates what `http verb` to use when making the API call. This supports `GET`,`POST`,`PUT`,`DELETE` and `PATCH`.

**Example:**

```json
{
    "uri":"https://myexampleapi.com/v0/baseid/tablename/",
    "method":"GET"
}
```

Title: Headers
Authentication
Content:
Authentication - This API takes different API authentication requests -

1. Basic Authentication
    - Standard
    - Extended (custom - s4)
2. API Token
3. Bearer Token

Title: **Basic Authentication**
Content: **Basic Authentication** - There are two types of `basic authentication`, `basic` and `basic_extended`.

Title: # Basic Authentication type 'basic'
# Basic Authentication type 'basic_extended'
Content:
# Basic Authentication type 'basic_extended' - Extended `Basic authentication` takes few more additional parameters on top of user name and password for the API and returns a header. Also a `custom_flow` property needs to be defined to identify which extended model to use (currently `s4` in the only one available).

**S4 model**
S4 model requires _login url_ (supplied as `token_url`), _token location_ (`token_location` indicates where the returned token can be found upon calling the `login` endpoint), http request method (`GET` or `POST`) and `custom_flow`:`s4` to indicate the model to use.

**Example:**

```json
{
    "uri":"https://myexampleapi.com/v0/[BASE ID]/[TABLE NAME]/",
    "method":"GET",
    "authentication":{
            "type":"basic_extended",
            "auth_parameters": {
                "token_method": "GET",
                "username": "john@example.com",
                "password": "abc123",
                "token_url": "https://myexampleapi.com/account/login",
                "token_location": "['SessionID']",
                "custom_flow": "s4"                
                }             
            }
}
```

The above example, where a call to the `https://myexampleapi.com/account/login` endpoint with basic authentication returns a `JSON` object with `SessionID` in the root element of that `JSON`. `token_location` indicates where to find that session id, which then gets used in rest of the associated calls.

parameters

Loop
Content: Loop - Loop option allows multiple API calls and fetch data from them. Only **two** level of loop hierarchy is supported, and this  allows multiple values to be dynamically modified in the provided `uri`. Loop option takes `filter` property, which contains the loops hierarchy, `level_1` and `level_2` (when required). Within the `level_[x]`, there is a `type` properties (_currently support only **three** types, `url_parameter`, `date` and `date_list`_). The number of loop is determined by the `array` passed in the `filters.level_[x].values` property for the first item in the `filters.level_[x]` array. Position of the dynamic values are determine by the `name` of `filters` list. Loop varaible in the uri or paramters to be represented within `{}` brackets, e.g. `https://myexampleapi.com/api/v1/{baseid}/` where `{baseid}` is the loop variable.

Title: Loop type `url_parameter`
Loop type `date`
Loop type `date_list`
Loop type `api_list`
Loop type `api_list_ext`
Pagination
Content: Pagination - `Pagination` parameter can be provided for API that support pagination. Currently support only `offset` pagination type.

Title: offset
Storage
Content: Storage - Storage refers to the output of the API call. `storage` property tells the service whether to return the result as `JSON` or store the result to other services, e.g., s3 bucket or azure blob storage. Currently only the `full_json` and `azure_blob` are supported. This takes **two** key parameters, `storage_plan` and `storage_type`. `storage_plan` is used in looped query, it indicates whether to save each loop result or wait till all the loops are done and save the entire data set as a single file. This takes one of **two** values, `single` or `loop` . `storage_type` indicates whether to return the response data as `JSON` or save the response to a cloud storage.
